### Binary Tree Count Function
#### Description
This is a C++ function that calculates the number of full binary trees with n vertices.

#### Code

```cpp
/**
 * @file binaryTreeCount.h
 * @brief Calculate the number of full binary trees with n vertices.
 */
#ifndef BINARYTREECOUNT_H
#define BINARYTREECOUNT_H

#include <iostream>

// Function to calculate the number of full binary trees with n vertices.
int B_n(int n);

#endif  // BINARYTREECOUNT_H

// Function to get the number of full binary trees.
int B_n(int n) {
    // Base cases
    if (n == 0) return 1;
    if (n == 1) return 1;
    if (n == 2) return 1;

    // Initialize an array to store the dynamic programming values
    int dp[n + 1][2];

    // Initialize first two rows
    for (int i = 0; i <= n; i++) {
        dp[i][0] = 1;
        if (i == 1) dp[i][1] = 1;
        else if (i == 2) dp[i][1] = 2;
    }

    // Fill up the rest of the table
    for (int i = 3; i <= n; i++) {
        // For each row, consider the current node and the two child nodes
        dp[i][0] = dp[i - 1][0];
        dp[i][1] = dp[i - 1][1] + dp[i - 2][1];
    }

    // Return the number of full binary trees with n vertices
    return dp[n][1];
}

int main() {
    // Example usage:
    std::cout << "Number of full binary trees with 5 vertices: " << B_n(5) << std::endl;
    return 0;
}

```

### Explanation
This function uses dynamic programming to calculate the number of full binary trees with n vertices by considering all possible combinations of nodes with zero and two children. We first calculate the base cases (0, 1, and 2 vertices) to initialize the dynamic programming table. Then, for each row i from 3 to n, we calculate the number of full binary trees with i vertices by considering the number of full binary trees with i - 1 vertices and i - 2 vertices (with and without the root node).

### Example Use Cases

*   The function can be used to calculate the number of full binary trees with a given number of vertices, as shown in the example usage in the main function.
*   It can also be used to calculate the total number of binary trees (full or non-full) with a given number of vertices.

### Time Complexity
The time complexity of this function is O(n^2), where n is the number of vertices, because we have a nested loop structure with n iterations.

### Space Complexity
The space complexity of this function is also O(n^2) due to the dynamic programming table (2n+1 elements) and the recursive call stack.

